{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511832"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:46:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:46:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11790"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11790"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.56,0.11,0.07,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4404"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43591"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4404"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11790"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28607"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1284"},{"type":"tags","id":"3077"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6241"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6246"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43591"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old woman presents to her usual neurologist for review. She has a medical history of Parkinson\u0027s Disease. Her medications include levodopa/carbidopa 250/25 mg three times daily. She states that her medication seems to be wearing off faster than previously. She asks if there is an additional medication that can be added to help. The neurologist suggests that pramipexole, a dopamine agonist, may be of benefit.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following side effects must the patient be informed about?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urinary retention","Impulse control disorder","Weight gain","Confusion","Somnolence"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMost patients with Parkinson disease on levodopa therapy eventually develop motor complications, including different patterns of motor fluctuations like the \u2018wearing off\u2019 phenomenon. To manage \u2018wearing off\u2019 of therapy, options include: combining levodopa and a dopamine agonist, using modified-release levodopa, or giving smaller, more frequent doses of levodopa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDopamine agonists can increase the risk of \u003Cstrong\u003Eimpulse control disorder \u003C/strong\u003Ewhich can. present as hypersexuality, gambling and alcohol use disorders. Patients must be screened for impulse control disorders prior to commencing dopamine agonists.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESomnolence \u003C/strong\u003Eis a potential side effect of levodopa/carbidopa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary retention\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Econfusion \u003C/strong\u003Eare potential side effects of anticholinergic medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeight gain \u003C/strong\u003Eis a common side effect of atypical antipsychotics (which do also have some dopaminergic activity).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dopamine agonists can increase the risk of hypersexuality, gambling and alcohol use disorders."],"references":["Talati R, Baker WL, Patel AA, Reinhart K, Coleman CI. Adding a dopamine agonist to preexisting levodopa therapy vs. levodopa therapy alone in advanced Parkinson\u0027s disease: a meta analysis. Int J Clin Pract. 2009;63(4):613-23. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK77241/#:~:text=All%20dopamine%20agonists%3A%20Dopamine%20agonists,WMD%20%2D5.56%2C%2095%25%20CI","Waller S, Williams L, Morales-Brice\u00f1o H, Fung VS. The initial diagnosis and management of Parkinson\u0027s disease. Aust J Gen Pract. 2021;50(11):793-800.  Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34713282/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28607"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11790"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28607"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-23T14:12:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-23T14:12:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4404"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43591"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1284"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Review","synonyms":[],"description":null,"positi